SELinux stands for Security-Enhanced Linux.
It is a security architecture for Linux system that allows administrators to have more control over who can access the system.
 
 
Enable Disable SELinux: :
               1.Enabled
                        A.Active/Enforcing  - Permissions denials are both logged and enforsed.
                        B.Permissive - Permissions denials are logged but not enforsed. In permissive mode instade of enforcing security policy, it prints warning.
               2.Disabled 
                        In this mode no SELinux policy is loaded.         
                  
          
commands :
          getinforce = To enforce the policy
          sestatus = To get information about the current status of SELinux
          setenforce = You can modify the mode SELinux is running in
                        eg. sudo setenforce permissive
                              sestatus
                              getenforce
                        eg. sudo setenforce Enforcing
                              sestatus
          
